{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784188658954,"sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_f71111be6eae4df285279cff","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Command Router Template\n3: description: Canonical skeleton for thin router commands with owned assets and presentation boundaries.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"command router template\"\n6:   - \"thin router command\"\n7:   - \"router presentation split\"\n8:   - \"router command skeleton\"\n9:   - \"owned assets presentation boundary\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.0.0.0\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Command Router Template\n16: \n17: Canonical skeleton for a first-class **router** command: a thin dispatcher whose `.md`\n18: verifies the orchestrating agent, resolves mode and arguments, then hands off to owned\n19: assets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). The\n20: router carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n21: \n22: ---\n23: \n24: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n25: \n26: Copy the skeleton below and fill the placeholders. Use it whenever `create-command`\n27: Step 11 classifies the command as a router.\n28: \n29: - **Blocking core (required):** `OWNED ASSETS` and `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`.\n30: - **Recommended (non-blocking warnings when absent):** `ROUTER CONTRACT`, `MODE ROUTING`,\n31:   `EXECUTION TARGETS`, `WORKFLOW SUMMARY`.\n32: - **Numbering:** H2 headers use `## N.` with full integers only, in the canonical order.\n33: - **Vocabulary is fixed.** Do not substitute synonyms such as `Routing Assets`,\n34:   `Workflow Routing`, or `Execution Order`; the validator alias-normalizes those as a\n35:   safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names below.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. CANONICAL SKELETON\n40: \n41: ```markdown\n42: ---\n43: description: <action-oriented single-line description, modes noted>\n44: argument-hint: \"<required> [:auto|:confirm] [optional] [--flag]\"\n45: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob\n46: ---\n47: \n48: # <Command Title>\n49: \n50: Thin router for <workflow>. This command verifies the orchestrating agent, resolves the\n51: execution mode, loads the presentation contract, then executes the owned assets.\n52: \n53: ## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n54: \n55: Do not dispatch agents or write artifacts from this Markdown file; that behavior is owned\n56: by the workflow/script assets. Load the presentation contract before showing any startup\n57: question, checkpoint, dashboard, success output, failure output, or next-step prompt.\n58: \n59: ---\n60: \n61: ## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n62: \n63: | Purpose | Asset |\n64: |---------|-------|\n65: | Presentation source of truth | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_presentation.txt` |\n66: | Auto workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_auto.yaml` |\n67: | Confirm workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_confirm.yaml` |\n68: \n69: ---\n70: \n71: ## 3. MODE ROUTING\n72: \n73: 1. Parse `$ARGUMENTS` for `:auto` / `:confirm` (and any command-specific mode suffixes).\n74: 2. Treat remaining flags as workflow inputs, not execution modes.\n75: 3. If no mode suffix is present, use the presentation contract's startup prompt to ask.\n76: 4. Load the selected execution target and run it step by step.\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n81: \n82: | Mode | Target |\n83: |------|--------|\n84: | `:auto` | `<auto workflow YAML, or the script/tool the router dispatches>` |\n85: | `:confirm` or interactive choice | `<confirm workflow YAML, or the interactive path>` |\n86: \n87: ---\n88: \n89: ## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n90: \n91: The following content lives only in the presentation asset, never inline in this router:\n92: \n93: - Startup-question wording and reply format.\n94: - Checkpoint and dashboard display templates.\n95: - Success and failure result templates.\n96: - Next-step suggestions and final user prompt wording.\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n101: \n102: A short, numbered recap of the end-to-end flow the router orchestrates, pointing at the\n103: owned assets rather than restating their content.\n104: ```\n105: \n106: ---\n107: \n108: ## 3. VARIANTS\n109: \n110: One router type; the variants differ only by hand-off, never by required sections.\n111: \n112: | Variant | Hand-off | Example families | Notes |\n113: |---------|----------|------------------|-------|\n114: | Workflow-YAML-backed | Router routes modes into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` | speckit, create, deep-large | Keep `EXECUTION TARGETS` pointing at the YAML assets. |\n115: | Direct-dispatch-script | Router dispatches straight to tools or scripts | memory, doctor, skill-benchmark | No workflow YAML; recommended sections may stay as warnings. |\n116: | Compiled-stub | Contract rendered at invocation from a compiled source | — (retained; none active) | Carries a `render-command-contract` marker; exempt from authored section requirements — do not hand-write section headings. |\n117: \n118: ---\n119: \n120: ## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n121: \n122: - `command_template.md` - exhaustive command type templates and vocabulary.\n123: - `command_presentation_template.md` - full `_presentation.txt` skeleton for the owned presentation asset.\n124: - `../SKILL.md` Step 11 - the first-class router authoring workflow.\n\n(End of file - total 124 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Command Router Template\ndescription: Canonical skeleton for thin router commands with owned assets and presentation boundaries.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"command router template\"\n  - \"thin router command\"\n  - \"router presentation split\"\n  - \"router command skeleton\"\n  - \"owned assets presentation boundary\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Command Router Template\n\nCanonical skeleton for a first-class **router** command: a thin dispatcher whose `.md`\nverifies the orchestrating agent, resolves mode and arguments, then hands off to owned\nassets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). The\nrouter carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Command Router Template\ndescription: Canonical skeleton for thin router commands with owned assets and presentation boundaries.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"command router template\"\n  - \"thin router command\"\n  - \"router presentation split\"\n  - \"router command skeleton\"\n  - \"owned assets presentation boundary\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Command Router Template\n\nCanonical skeleton for a first-class **router** command: a thin dispatcher whose `.md`\nverifies the orchestrating agent, resolves mode and arguments, then hands off to owned\nassets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). The\nrouter carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nCopy the skeleton below and fill the placeholders. Use it whenever `create-command`\nStep 11 classifies the command as a router.\n\n- **Blocking core (required):** `OWNED ASSETS` and `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`.\n- **Recommended (non-blocking warnings when absent):** `ROUTER CONTRACT`, `MODE ROUTING`,\n  `EXECUTION TARGETS`, `WORKFLOW SUMMARY`.\n- **Numbering:** H2 headers use `## N.` with full integers only, in the canonical order.\n- **Vocabulary is fixed.** Do not substitute synonyms such as `Routing Assets`,\n  `Workflow Routing`, or `Execution Order`; the validator alias-normalizes those as a\n  safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names below.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CANONICAL SKELETON\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: <action-oriented single-line description, modes noted>\nargument-hint: \"<required> [:auto|:confirm] [optional] [--flag]\"\nallowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob\n---\n\n# <Command Title>\n\nThin router for <workflow>. This command verifies the orchestrating agent, resolves the\nexecution mode, loads the presentation contract, then executes the owned assets.\n\n## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n\nDo not dispatch agents or write artifacts from this Markdown file; that behavior is owned\nby the workflow/script assets. Load the presentation contract before showing any startup\nquestion, checkpoint, dashboard, success output, failure output, or next-step prompt.\n\n---\n\n## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n\n| Purpose | Asset |\n|---------|-------|\n| Presentation source of truth | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_presentation.txt` |\n| Auto workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_auto.yaml` |\n| Confirm workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_confirm.yaml` |\n\n---\n\n## 3. MODE ROUTING\n\n1. Parse `$ARGUMENTS` for `:auto` / `:confirm` (and any command-specific mode suffixes).\n2. Treat remaining flags as workflow inputs, not execution modes.\n3. If no mode suffix is present, use the presentation contract's startup prompt to ask.\n4. Load the selected execution target and run it step by step.\n\n---\n\n## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n\n| Mode | Target |\n|------|--------|\n| `:auto` | `<auto workflow YAML, or the script/tool the router dispatches>` |\n| `:confirm` or interactive choice | `<confirm workflow YAML, or the interactive path>` |\n\n---\n\n## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n\nThe following content lives only in the presentation asset, never inline in this router:\n\n- Startup-question wording and reply format.\n- Checkpoint and dashboard display templates.\n- Success and failure result templates.\n- Next-step suggestions and final user prompt wording.\n\n---\n\n## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n\nA short, numbered recap of the end-to-end flow the router orchestrates, pointing at the\nowned assets rather than restating their content.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. VARIANTS\n\nOne router type; the variants differ only by hand-off, never by required sections.\n\n| Variant | Hand-off | Example families | Notes |\n|---------|----------|------------------|-------|\n| Workflow-YAML-backed | Router routes modes into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` | speckit, create, deep-large | Keep `EXECUTION TARGETS` pointing at the YAML assets. |\n| Direct-dispatch-script | Router dispatches straight to tools or scripts | memory, doctor, skill-benchmark | No workflow YAML; recommended sections may stay as warnings. |\n| Compiled-stub | Contract rendered at invocation from a compiled source | — (retained; none active) | Carries a `render-command-contract` marker; exempt from authored section requirements — do not hand-write section headings. |\n\n---\n\n## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `command_template.md` - exhaustive command type templates and vocabulary.\n- `command_presentation_template.md` - full `_presentation.txt` skeleton for the owned presentation asset.\n- `../SKILL.md` Step 11 - the first-class router authoring workflow.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":124,"totalLines":124,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md","time":{"start":1784188658947,"end":1784188658952}},"id":"prt_f69ee64ff001wSL7T3n3QE4qJb","sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","messageID":"msg_f69edaa1c0017e8kNFRGKDgIap"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1784188659998,"sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","part":{"id":"prt_f69ee691b001XViytOgzi4D5gt","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","messageID":"msg_f69edaa1c0017e8kNFRGKDgIap","sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":106494,"input":2393,"output":93,"reasoning":776,"cache":{"write":0,"read":103232}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784188690499,"sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","part":{"id":"prt_f69eee03d001R3xNaz5c39wl6J","messageID":"msg_f69ee6d71001d18K2diu2lvBf7","sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1784188695540,"sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","part":{"id":"prt_f69eef3ec001DmE5btI4FbdMyH","messageID":"msg_f69ee6d71001d18K2diu2lvBf7","sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","type":"text","text":"Now the memory inline-presentation case, a presentation.txt sample, and the deep fat-router for RQ2/RQ5.","time":{"start":1784188695532,"end":1784188695538}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784188695544,"sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7badeb29a42c48e782939b59","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/memory/search.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/memory/search.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: description: Unified continuity retrieval: spec-doc search, baselines, memory causal graph, ablations, dashboards.\n3: argument-hint: \"<query> [--intent <type>|--intent=<type>] | preflight <specFolder> <taskId> | postflight <specFolder> <taskId> | history <specFolder> | causal <memoryId> | link <sourceId> <targetId> <relation> | unlink <edgeId> | causal-stats | ablation | dashboard\"\n4: allowed-tools: Read, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_context, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_quick_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_match_triggers, mcp__mk_spec_memory__task_preflight, mcp__mk_spec_memory__task_postflight, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_drift_why, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_link, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_stats, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_unlink, mcp__mk_spec_memory__eval_run_ablation, mcp__mk_spec_memory__eval_reporting_dashboard, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_get_learning_history, mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_query, mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_context\n5: ---\n6: \n7: # /memory:search\n8: \n9: Thin router for memory retrieval and analysis.\n10: \n11: ## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n12: \n13: > **Contract register (COSTAR).** This contract is written objective-first for an automated-pipeline audience: a fixed response shape, no preamble, no conversational framing inside the rendered block. Weak instruction-followers tolerate this register best, so it is the contract's own wording style — not a prompt framework imposed on callers, and not a single global framework applied to every command.\n14: \n15: Argument resolution (deterministic, read this first). The shell line below is evaluated before you read any policy. It is the ground truth for this invocation. The renderer substitutes the raw query text where `$ARGUMENTS` appears as one positional argument after `--`, so the wrapper treats shell metacharacters in the query (`*`, `$(…)`, backticks, `;`, `|`) as literal query text. The wrapper then joins the provided positional argument into one string and reports whether any argument was supplied.\n16: \n17: !`bash -c 'if [ \"$#\" -gt 0 ]; then q=\"$*\"; q=\"${q//\\\"/\\\\\\\"}\"; printf \"ARGS_PRESENT=true\\nQUERY=\\\"%s\\\"\\n\" \"$q\"; else printf \"ARGS_PRESENT=false\\nQUERY=\\\"\\\"\\n\"; fi' -- '$ARGUMENTS'`\n18: \n19: Bind your control flow to the two values above — never re-derive arg-presence from your own reading of the prompt:\n20: \n21: - **When `ARGS_PRESENT=true`: you MUST execute retrieval (or the analysis route) on `QUERY` now.** Do NOT ask the startup question, and do NOT treat a populated `QUERY` as empty. Go to the retrieval route in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS, or the analysis route in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS when the first token of `QUERY` is a known analysis subcommand.\n22: - **ONLY IF `ARGS_PRESENT=false`:** follow startup routing in §3 MODE ROUTING and ask the one open-ended question.\n23: \n24: Guardrails:\n25: - Do not infer a query from prior conversation when `ARGS_PRESENT=false`; ask the open-ended startup question.\n26: - Ask targeted follow-up questions only when the query is genuinely ambiguous.\n27: - Do not display the old option dump at startup.\n28: - Do not use forbidden memory/result labels listed in the presentation asset.\n29: - Do not open raw SQLite or edit memory DB files.\n30: - This is a direct-dispatch command with no workflow YAML by design; do not create or modify workflow YAML from this command.\n31: \n32: ## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n33: \n34: | Asset | Path | Purpose |\n35: | --- | --- | --- |\n36: | Presentation | `.opencode/commands/memory/assets/search_presentation.txt` | Startup question policy, analysis overview, result tables, empty-result fallback, and clean GPT-via-opencode display rules. |\n37: \n38: This is a direct-dispatch command: it routes straight to the memory and code-graph MCP tools and owns no workflow YAML by design. There is no `_auto`/`_confirm` workflow YAML for the memory family and none is missing.\n39: \n40: Before asking startup questions or displaying results, read the presentation asset and use it as the display source of truth.\n41: \n42: ## 3. MODE ROUTING\n43: \n44: Execution order:\n45: \n46: 1. Read the §1 ROUTER CONTRACT argument-resolution output: `ARGS_PRESENT` and `QUERY` are already computed for you.\n47: 2. Read `.opencode/commands/memory/assets/search_presentation.txt` before rendering any response.\n48: 3. **If `ARGS_PRESENT=true`:** route `QUERY` to the retrieval route (§4 EXECUTION TARGETS), or to the analysis route (§4 EXECUTION TARGETS) when the first token of `QUERY` is a known analysis subcommand. Execute now — do NOT ask the startup question.\n49: 4. **ONLY IF `ARGS_PRESENT=false`:** follow startup routing (below) and ask the one open-ended question.\n50: 5. Render the response from the presentation contract; retrieval results must use the inline contract in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS.\n51: \n52: Startup routing. **Reach this ONLY IF `ARGS_PRESENT=false`.** A populated `QUERY` never reaches here — if `ARGS_PRESENT=true`, you already executed the retrieval or analysis route in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS. When `ARGS_PRESENT=false`, ask one open-ended question from the presentation asset. Do not dump the full intent/menu list at startup. Treat a custom answer as the retrieval query.\n53: \n54: ## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n55: \n56: ### Retrieval route\n57: \n58: Enter this route when `ARGS_PRESENT=true` and `QUERY` is not an analysis subcommand. Parse an optional `--intent <type>` or `--intent=<type>` from `QUERY`; otherwise let the server or local router infer intent from the query.\n59: \n60: 1. Extract `query` (the resolved `QUERY`) and optional intent override.\n61: 2. Prefer `memory_context({ input: query, mode: \"auto\", intent, limit: 10, enableDedup: true })`.\n62: 3. Use `memory_quick_search` for fast query-only fallback.\n63: 4. Use `memory_search` only when fine-grained search parameters are needed.\n64: 5. Use `memory_match_triggers` as a supplemental fallback, not as a replacement for direct retrieval.\n65: 6. For structural code questions, use the stable code-graph tools before semantic or lexical memory channels when available.\n66: 7. Render compact, parseable output using the presentation asset and the contract below.\n67: \n68: MUST emit exactly this shape for retrieval results:\n69: \n70: ```text\n71: MEMORY:SEARCH \"<query>\" intent=<detected_intent> results=<count>\n72: --------------------------------------------------\n73: <specFolder>/\n74:   <score>  #<id>  <title>\n75:   <score>  #<id>  <title>\n76: \n77: <specFolder>/\n78:   <score>  #<id>  <title>\n79: \n80: STATUS=OK RESULTS=<count> INTENT=<detected_intent>\n81: ```\n82: \n83: Core-slot mandate: every retrieval response MUST render all five core slots — (1) the query echo `\"<query>\"`, (2) the `<score>` similarity, (3) `#<id>`, (4) `<title>`, and (5) the `STATUS` footer carrying `RESULTS` and `INTENT`. None is optional; the only exception is an empty result set, which uses the empty-result fallback in the presentation asset.\n84: \n85: Score mandate — one score, one scale, one name: `<score>` is `similarity` on a 0–1 scale rendered to two decimals (`0.79`), and it is the SOLE ranking metric per row. Never render `confidence`, and never render a percentage — divide any percentage-scaled value by 100 before emitting (`79.44` → `0.79`). Do not add a second ranking number under any other name.\n86: \n87: Arg-echo rule: the query echoed in `\"<query>\"` MUST equal the resolved `QUERY`. A mismatch means the query was dropped — re-emit with `QUERY`.\n88: \n89: Surface-parity clause: the five core slots and the similarity 0–1 / two-decimal scale are mandatory when this command contract is loaded through `--command` dispatch or another route that explicitly reads the presentation asset. Raw one-shot natural-language prompts that bypass this command contract cannot guarantee the same render policy. Conversational phrasing may wrap the block in prose, but once this contract is loaded the core field set, field names, and scale never change.\n90: \n91: Verdict render slots: `requestQuality` and `citationPolicy` are the only sanctioned extras beyond the core slots. When present, render each as a named trailing field per the presentation asset, never as an unnamed, renamed, or ad-hoc metric, and their presence must be unambiguous.\n92: \n93: Under the default contract their absence is valid. `SPECKIT_ENVELOPE_FIDELITY` is default-ON; set it to `false`, `0`, or `off` to opt out. When enabled, the two fields become conditionally-mandatory render slots, required-when-present: a verdict field the tool response carries MUST appear unaltered in the rendered block, and the tool ships a ready-to-paste `data.envelopeRender` fragment the render pastes verbatim instead of transcribing the fields.\n94: \n95: Self-check: before finishing, verify the emitted block includes the `MEMORY:SEARCH` header, all five core slots, and the `STATUS` footer, and that no row carries `confidence` or a percentage score. When envelope fidelity is enabled, also verify that every verdict field the tool response carries (`requestQuality` and `citationPolicy`) is present in the rendered block, and re-emit from `data.envelopeRender` any verdict field the tool shipped but the render dropped.\n96: \n97: Supported intents:\n98: - `add_feature`\n99: - `fix_bug`\n100: - `refactor`\n101: - `security_audit`\n102: - `understand`\n103: - `find_spec`\n104: - `find_decision`\n105: \n106: ### Analysis route\n107: \n108: Enter this route when `ARGS_PRESENT=true` and the first token of `QUERY` is one of the analysis subcommands below.\n109: \n110: Known analysis subcommands:\n111: - `preflight`\n112: - `postflight`\n113: - `history`\n114: - `causal`\n115: - `link`\n116: - `unlink`\n117: - `causal-stats`\n118: - `ablation`\n119: - `dashboard`\n120: \n121: | Subcommand | Tool | Purpose |\n122: | --- | --- | --- |\n123: | `preflight <specFolder> <taskId>` | `task_preflight` | Capture epistemic baseline. |\n124: | `postflight <specFolder> <taskId>` | `task_postflight` | Capture learning delta. |\n125: | `history <specFolder>` | `memory_get_learning_history` | Show learning cycles. |\n126: | `causal <memoryId>` | `memory_drift_why` | Trace decision lineage. |\n127: | `link <sourceId> <targetId> <relation>` | `memory_causal_link` | Create causal relation. |\n128: | `unlink <edgeId>` | `memory_causal_unlink` | Remove causal relation. |\n129: | `causal-stats` | `memory_causal_stats` | Show graph coverage. |\n130: | `ablation` | `eval_run_ablation` | Run enabled channel ablation through the eval harness. The active DB lets the harness reject a cold or incomplete golden-set vector index before scoring. |\n131: | `dashboard` | `eval_reporting_dashboard` | Show stored eval snapshot trends and channel metrics. Stored ablation runs carry the diagnostic gate-verdict, calibration and cold-lane payload in baseline metadata. |\n132: \n133: `ablation` invokes `eval_run_ablation` with the active DB and diagnostic snapshots enabled. It may fail before scoring when the coverage guard finds golden-set parent embeddings below the threshold. The recovery is corpus reindex plus embedding reconcile, then the ground-truth remap if alignment still drifts.\n134: \n135: `dashboard` invokes `eval_reporting_dashboard` against stored eval snapshots. It reports persisted metric trends and channel breakdowns. C9 gate-verdict and calibration values are produced by stored ablation runs in the baseline metadata. They are not recomputed by the dashboard command.\n136: \n137: ## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n138: \n139: The full presentation contract lives in `.opencode/commands/memory/assets/search_presentation.txt`. This router may only inline the compressed retrieval result shape above as a hard render reminder.\n140: \n141: The following content must come from the presentation asset, not from router prose:\n142: \n143: - Empty-argument startup question and targeted follow-up wording.\n144: - Analysis overview, preflight, postflight, history, causal, link, unlink, causal-stats, ablation, dashboard, empty-result, and error displays.\n145: - Forbidden vocabulary, result labels, fallback labels, examples, and recovery text.\n146: - Verdict render-slot placement, exact field names (`requestQuality` and `citationPolicy`), the conditionally-mandatory required-when-present rule, and the `data.envelopeRender` paste fragment.\n147: \n148: ## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n149: \n150: The router binds control flow to the deterministic `ARGS_PRESENT`/`QUERY` resolution: with arguments present it dispatches the retrieval route (memory context/search tools plus code-graph tools, rendered through the fixed five-core-slot contract) or the analysis route (preflight, postflight, history, causal, link, unlink, causal-stats, ablation, dashboard) when the first token is a known subcommand; with no arguments it asks the one open-ended startup question. Every user-facing string renders through the presentation asset. It is a direct-dispatch command with no workflow YAML by design.\n151: \n152: Related commands: `/memory:save` (save conversation context); `/memory:manage` (database management, checkpoints, ingest, retention, and health); `/memory:learn` (constitutional rules); `/speckit:resume` (session recovery and continuation).\n\n(End of file - total 152 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ndescription: Unified continuity retrieval: spec-doc search, baselines, memory causal graph, ablations, dashboards.\nargument-hint: \"<query> [--intent <type>|--intent=<type>] | preflight <specFolder> <taskId> | postflight <specFolder> <taskId> | history <specFolder> | causal <memoryId> | link <sourceId> <targetId> <relation> | unlink <edgeId> | causal-stats | ablation | dashboard\"\nallowed-tools: Read, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_context, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_quick_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_match_triggers, mcp__mk_spec_memory__task_preflight, mcp__mk_spec_memory__task_postflight, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_drift_why, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_link, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_stats, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_unlink, mcp__mk_spec_memory__eval_run_ablation, mcp__mk_spec_memory__eval_reporting_dashboard, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_get_learning_history, mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_query, mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_context\n---\n\n# /memory:search\n\nThin router for memory retrieval and analysis.\n\n## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n\n> **Contract register (COSTAR).** This contract is written objective-first for an automated-pipeline audience: a fixed response shape, no preamble, no conversational framing inside the rendered block. Weak instruction-followers tolerate this register best, so it is the contract's own wording style — not a prompt framework imposed on callers, and not a single global framework applied to every command.\n\nArgument resolution (deterministic, read this first). The shell line below is evaluated before you read any policy. It is the ground truth for this invocation. The renderer substitutes the raw query text where `$ARGUMENTS` appears as one positional argument after `--`, so the wrapper treats shell metacharacters in the query (`*`, `$(…)`, backticks, `;`, `|`) as literal query text. The wrapper then joins the provided positional argument into one string and reports whether any argument was supplied.\n\n!`bash -c 'if [ \"$#\" -gt 0 ]; then q=\"$*\"; q=\"${q//\\\"/\\\\\\\"}\"; printf \"ARGS_PRESENT=true\\nQUERY=\\\"%s\\\"\\n\" \"$q\"; else printf \"ARGS_PRESENT=false\\nQUERY=\\\"\\\"\\n\"; fi' -- '$ARGUMENTS'`\n\nBind your control flow to the two values above — never re-derive arg-presence from your own reading of the prompt:\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/memory/search.md","text":"---\ndescription: Unified continuity retrieval: spec-doc search, baselines, memory causal graph, ablations, dashboards.\nargument-hint: \"<query> [--intent <type>|--intent=<type>] | preflight <specFolder> <taskId> | postflight <specFolder> <taskId> | history <specFolder> | causal <memoryId> | link <sourceId> <targetId> <relation> | unlink <edgeId> | causal-stats | ablation | dashboard\"\nallowed-tools: Read, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_context, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_quick_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_match_triggers, mcp__mk_spec_memory__task_preflight, mcp__mk_spec_memory__task_postflight, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_drift_why, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_link, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_stats, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_causal_unlink, mcp__mk_spec_memory__eval_run_ablation, mcp__mk_spec_memory__eval_reporting_dashboard, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_get_learning_history, mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_query, mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_context\n---\n\n# /memory:search\n\nThin router for memory retrieval and analysis.\n\n## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n\n> **Contract register (COSTAR).** This contract is written objective-first for an automated-pipeline audience: a fixed response shape, no preamble, no conversational framing inside the rendered block. Weak instruction-followers tolerate this register best, so it is the contract's own wording style — not a prompt framework imposed on callers, and not a single global framework applied to every command.\n\nArgument resolution (deterministic, read this first). The shell line below is evaluated before you read any policy. It is the ground truth for this invocation. The renderer substitutes the raw query text where `$ARGUMENTS` appears as one positional argument after `--`, so the wrapper treats shell metacharacters in the query (`*`, `$(…)`, backticks, `;`, `|`) as literal query text. The wrapper then joins the provided positional argument into one string and reports whether any argument was supplied.\n\n!`bash -c 'if [ \"$#\" -gt 0 ]; then q=\"$*\"; q=\"${q//\\\"/\\\\\\\"}\"; printf \"ARGS_PRESENT=true\\nQUERY=\\\"%s\\\"\\n\" \"$q\"; else printf \"ARGS_PRESENT=false\\nQUERY=\\\"\\\"\\n\"; fi' -- '$ARGUMENTS'`\n\nBind your control flow to the two values above — never re-derive arg-presence from your own reading of the prompt:\n\n- **When `ARGS_PRESENT=true`: you MUST execute retrieval (or the analysis route) on `QUERY` now.** Do NOT ask the startup question, and do NOT treat a populated `QUERY` as empty. Go to the retrieval route in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS, or the analysis route in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS when the first token of `QUERY` is a known analysis subcommand.\n- **ONLY IF `ARGS_PRESENT=false`:** follow startup routing in §3 MODE ROUTING and ask the one open-ended question.\n\nGuardrails:\n- Do not infer a query from prior conversation when `ARGS_PRESENT=false`; ask the open-ended startup question.\n- Ask targeted follow-up questions only when the query is genuinely ambiguous.\n- Do not display the old option dump at startup.\n- Do not use forbidden memory/result labels listed in the presentation asset.\n- Do not open raw SQLite or edit memory DB files.\n- This is a direct-dispatch command with no workflow YAML by design; do not create or modify workflow YAML from this command.\n\n## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n\n| Asset | Path | Purpose |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Presentation | `.opencode/commands/memory/assets/search_presentation.txt` | Startup question policy, analysis overview, result tables, empty-result fallback, and clean GPT-via-opencode display rules. |\n\nThis is a direct-dispatch command: it routes straight to the memory and code-graph MCP tools and owns no workflow YAML by design. There is no `_auto`/`_confirm` workflow YAML for the memory family and none is missing.\n\nBefore asking startup questions or displaying results, read the presentation asset and use it as the display source of truth.\n\n## 3. MODE ROUTING\n\nExecution order:\n\n1. Read the §1 ROUTER CONTRACT argument-resolution output: `ARGS_PRESENT` and `QUERY` are already computed for you.\n2. Read `.opencode/commands/memory/assets/search_presentation.txt` before rendering any response.\n3. **If `ARGS_PRESENT=true`:** route `QUERY` to the retrieval route (§4 EXECUTION TARGETS), or to the analysis route (§4 EXECUTION TARGETS) when the first token of `QUERY` is a known analysis subcommand. Execute now — do NOT ask the startup question.\n4. **ONLY IF `ARGS_PRESENT=false`:** follow startup routing (below) and ask the one open-ended question.\n5. Render the response from the presentation contract; retrieval results must use the inline contract in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS.\n\nStartup routing. **Reach this ONLY IF `ARGS_PRESENT=false`.** A populated `QUERY` never reaches here — if `ARGS_PRESENT=true`, you already executed the retrieval or analysis route in §4 EXECUTION TARGETS. When `ARGS_PRESENT=false`, ask one open-ended question from the presentation asset. Do not dump the full intent/menu list at startup. Treat a custom answer as the retrieval query.\n\n## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n\n### Retrieval route\n\nEnter this route when `ARGS_PRESENT=true` and `QUERY` is not an analysis subcommand. Parse an optional `--intent <type>` or `--intent=<type>` from `QUERY`; otherwise let the server or local router infer intent from the query.\n\n1. Extract `query` (the resolved `QUERY`) and optional intent override.\n2. Prefer `memory_context({ input: query, mode: \"auto\", intent, limit: 10, enableDedup: true })`.\n3. Use `memory_quick_search` for fast query-only fallback.\n4. Use `memory_search` only when fine-grained search parameters are needed.\n5. Use `memory_match_triggers` as a supplemental fallback, not as a replacement for direct retrieval.\n6. For structural code questions, use the stable code-graph tools before semantic or lexical memory channels when available.\n7. Render compact, parseable output using the presentation asset and the contract below.\n\nMUST emit exactly this shape for retrieval results:\n\n```text\nMEMORY:SEARCH \"<query>\" intent=<detected_intent> results=<count>\n--------------------------------------------------\n<specFolder>/\n  <score>  #<id>  <title>\n  <score>  #<id>  <title>\n\n<specFolder>/\n  <score>  #<id>  <title>\n\nSTATUS=OK RESULTS=<count> INTENT=<detected_intent>\n```\n\nCore-slot mandate: every retrieval response MUST render all five core slots — (1) the query echo `\"<query>\"`, (2) the `<score>` similarity, (3) `#<id>`, (4) `<title>`, and (5) the `STATUS` footer carrying `RESULTS` and `INTENT`. None is optional; the only exception is an empty result set, which uses the empty-result fallback in the presentation asset.\n\nScore mandate — one score, one scale, one name: `<score>` is `similarity` on a 0–1 scale rendered to two decimals (`0.79`), and it is the SOLE ranking metric per row. Never render `confidence`, and never render a percentage — divide any percentage-scaled value by 100 before emitting (`79.44` → `0.79`). Do not add a second ranking number under any other name.\n\nArg-echo rule: the query echoed in `\"<query>\"` MUST equal the resolved `QUERY`. A mismatch means the query was dropped — re-emit with `QUERY`.\n\nSurface-parity clause: the five core slots and the similarity 0–1 / two-decimal scale are mandatory when this command contract is loaded through `--command` dispatch or another route that explicitly reads the presentation asset. Raw one-shot natural-language prompts that bypass this command contract cannot guarantee the same render policy. Conversational phrasing may wrap the block in prose, but once this contract is loaded the core field set, field names, and scale never change.\n\nVerdict render slots: `requestQuality` and `citationPolicy` are the only sanctioned extras beyond the core slots. When present, render each as a named trailing field per the presentation asset, never as an unnamed, renamed, or ad-hoc metric, and their presence must be unambiguous.\n\nUnder the default contract their absence is valid. `SPECKIT_ENVELOPE_FIDELITY` is default-ON; set it to `false`, `0`, or `off` to opt out. When enabled, the two fields become conditionally-mandatory render slots, required-when-present: a verdict field the tool response carries MUST appear unaltered in the rendered block, and the tool ships a ready-to-paste `data.envelopeRender` fragment the render pastes verbatim instead of transcribing the fields.\n\nSelf-check: before finishing, verify the emitted block includes the `MEMORY:SEARCH` header, all five core slots, and the `STATUS` footer, and that no row carries `confidence` or a percentage score. When envelope fidelity is enabled, also verify that every verdict field the tool response carries (`requestQuality` and `citationPolicy`) is present in the rendered block, and re-emit from `data.envelopeRender` any verdict field the tool shipped but the render dropped.\n\nSupported intents:\n- `add_feature`\n- `fix_bug`\n- `refactor`\n- `security_audit`\n- `understand`\n- `find_spec`\n- `find_decision`\n\n### Analysis route\n\nEnter this route when `ARGS_PRESENT=true` and the first token of `QUERY` is one of the analysis subcommands below.\n\nKnown analysis subcommands:\n- `preflight`\n- `postflight`\n- `history`\n- `causal`\n- `link`\n- `unlink`\n- `causal-stats`\n- `ablation`\n- `dashboard`\n\n| Subcommand | Tool | Purpose |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `preflight <specFolder> <taskId>` | `task_preflight` | Capture epistemic baseline. |\n| `postflight <specFolder> <taskId>` | `task_postflight` | Capture learning delta. |\n| `history <specFolder>` | `memory_get_learning_history` | Show learning cycles. |\n| `causal <memoryId>` | `memory_drift_why` | Trace decision lineage. |\n| `link <sourceId> <targetId> <relation>` | `memory_causal_link` | Create causal relation. |\n| `unlink <edgeId>` | `memory_causal_unlink` | Remove causal relation. |\n| `causal-stats` | `memory_causal_stats` | Show graph coverage. |\n| `ablation` | `eval_run_ablation` | Run enabled channel ablation through the eval harness. The active DB lets the harness reject a cold or incomplete golden-set vector index before scoring. |\n| `dashboard` | `eval_reporting_dashboard` | Show stored eval snapshot trends and channel metrics. Stored ablation runs carry the diagnostic gate-verdict, calibration and cold-lane payload in baseline metadata. |\n\n`ablation` invokes `eval_run_ablation` with the active DB and diagnostic snapshots enabled. It may fail before scoring when the coverage guard finds golden-set parent embeddings below the threshold. The recovery is corpus reindex plus embedding reconcile, then the ground-truth remap if alignment still drifts.\n\n`dashboard` invokes `eval_reporting_dashboard` against stored eval snapshots. It reports persisted metric trends and channel breakdowns. C9 gate-verdict and calibration values are produced by stored ablation runs in the baseline metadata. They are not recomputed by the dashboard command.\n\n## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n\nThe full presentation contract lives in `.opencode/commands/memory/assets/search_presentation.txt`. This router may only inline the compressed retrieval result shape above as a hard render reminder.\n\nThe following content must come from the presentation asset, not from router prose:\n\n- Empty-argument startup question and targeted follow-up wording.\n- Analysis overview, preflight, postflight, history, causal, link, unlink, causal-stats, ablation, dashboard, empty-result, and error displays.\n- Forbidden vocabulary, result labels, fallback labels, examples, and recovery text.\n- Verdict render-slot placement, exact field names (`requestQuality` and `citationPolicy`), the conditionally-mandatory required-when-present rule, and the `data.envelopeRender` paste fragment.\n\n## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n\nThe router binds control flow to the deterministic `ARGS_PRESENT`/`QUERY` resolution: with arguments present it dispatches the retrieval route (memory context/search tools plus code-graph tools, rendered through the fixed five-core-slot contract) or the analysis route (preflight, postflight, history, causal, link, unlink, causal-stats, ablation, dashboard) when the first token is a known subcommand; with no arguments it asks the one open-ended startup question. Every user-facing string renders through the presentation asset. It is a direct-dispatch command with no workflow YAML by design.\n\nRelated commands: `/memory:save` (save conversation context); `/memory:manage` (database management, checkpoints, ingest, retention, and health); `/memory:learn` (constitutional rules); `/speckit:resume` (session recovery and continuation).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":152,"totalLines":152,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/commands/memory/search.md","time":{"start":1784188695537,"end":1784188695542}},"id":"prt_f69eef3ee001P8hG7mzWGKQ2oe","sessionID":"ses_09619781bffeQ3oAZ5RFeTTgCJ","messageID":"msg_f69ee6d71001d18K2diu2lvBf7"}}
